Yes, it is possible to solve the problem without using loops or recursion. One way to do this is using the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm.

Here's how the algorithm works:

1. Generate all the positive integers less than or equal to n (i.e., n - 1, n - 2,..., 1).
2. For each of these integers, check if it is a multiple of 3. If it is, write it down.
3. If no multiple of 3 is found in the previous step, it means there is no multiple of 3 that is less than or equal to n. Therefore, n must be a power of 3.

Here's the Java implementation of the algorithm:
```java
public class PowerOfThree {
    public static boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        int[] primes = sieve(1, n);
        for (int i = 0; i < primes.length; i++) {
            if (primes[i] < 3) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

    private static int[] sieve(int n, int count) {
        boolean[] isPrime = new boolean[n + 1];
        Arrays.fill(isPrime, true);
        for (int i = 2; i * i <= n; i++) {
            if (isPrime[i]) {
                for (int j = i * i; j <= n; j += i) {
                    isPrime[j] = false;
                }
            }
        }
        return isPrime;
    }
}
```
In this implementation, the `sieve` method generates all the positive integers less than or equal to n using the Sieve of Eratosthenes algorithm, and returns an array of boolean values indicating whether each integer is a multiple of 3. The `isPowerOfThree` method checks if n is a power of 3 using the array returned by `sieve`. If n is not a power of 3, it returns false. If n is a power of 3, it returns true.

Note that this implementation has a time complexity of O(n log n), which is the worst-case time complexity of the algorithm. However, it is still an acceptable solution for small values of n.

